I remember my first attempt at photographing the iconic Trevi fountain years ago as a complete failure. That was a long time ago and it was of the better lessons I’ve learned over the years.
This is one of the places we usually take our groups on my Italy photo tour that I run in May.

2 spots left!  Italy Tour Details: See the link in my bio

The day before I took this photograph I attempted to get a shot of the fountain during the day and was stopped by two of Rome’s finest police officers. While hundreds of people were taking snapshots I was confronted by these 2 officers who told me it was forbidden to take photos in Rome with a tripod. Now I can understand needing a permit for a commercial shoot, in fact, I used them all the time when shooting commercially. It’s only fair to get a permit if you will be blocking a street, traffic or cause a distraction by photographing with a team in a public place. Over the next many years, I was to learn that tripods are universally hated by police and security guards all over the world but I digress.

As usual, things happen for a reason and I left the tourist-infested Trevi Fountain to console myself with a plate of gnocchi with gorgonzola cream sauce, a couple of glasses of relatively inexpensive but delicious Chianti and perhaps the most decadent sfogliatelle pastry in the history of Italy. Did I mention that the food on my Italy tour is decadently delectable? I've had the daunting task of vetting the restaurants for you. I know... tough job but someone has to do it!

Feeling much better I went off to photograph some other locations on my list and plotted to return to the fountain in a similar fashion of general MacArthur returning to the Philippines. I rose well before sunrise the next day in hopes of there not being any tourists or police at the Trevi Fountain and I was fifty percent lucky. Not a tourist in sight at 5 am, however, there was a police car with 2 officers in it. Since it was dark I could not tell if they had seen me or my wicked tripod so I meandered along nonchalantly in hopes of disguising my fiendish photographic intent. My ruse was a success! 🎄❄️ Merry Christmas and Happy Holidays! ❄️🎄 Hard to believe that another year is coming to an end but that only means that another one full of opportunity is just about to begin.

Thanks to everyone who took the time to send me private messages, cards, and Ferraris. It means a lot to me to know that you were thinking of me. 🤪

Hope that you're enjoying your holiday with loved ones and feeling peace in your lives.

Remember that this is the season for giving and that there are so many worthy causes in the world that need your support. 
This is the perfect time to support your favourite charities, call an old friend, tell someone that you love them, give a random hug, teach a kid something new, visit someone in the hospital, spend some quality time with your pets, create some art, or do anything else that feeds your soul and not your ego.

Wishing you all enough.

It's not that easy being green
Having to spend each day the color of the leaves
When I think it could be nicer being red, or yellow, or gold
Or something much more colorful like that

It's not easy being green
It seems you blend in with so many other ordinary things
And people tend to pass you over
'Cause you're not standing out
Like flashy sparkles in the water
Or stars in the sky

But green's the color of spring
And green can be cool and friendly-like
And green can be big like an ocean
Or important like a river
Or tall like a tree

When green is all there is to be
It could make you wonder why
But why wonder why wonder
I am green, and it'll do fine
It's beautiful, and I think it's what I want to be
——————————

“All the world's a stage,
And all the men and women merely players;
They have their exits and their entrances,
And one man in his time plays many parts,
His acts being seven ages. At first, the infant,
Mewling and puking in the nurse's arms.
Then the whining schoolboy, with his satchel
And shining morning face, creeping like snail
Unwillingly to school. And then the lover,
Sighing like furnace, with a woeful ballad
Made to his mistress' eyebrow. Then a soldier,
Full of strange oaths and bearded like the pard,
Jealous in honor, sudden and quick in quarrel,
Seeking the bubble reputation
Even in the cannon's mouth. And then the justice,
In fair round belly with good capon lined,
With eyes severe and beard of formal cut,
Full of wise saws and modern instances;
And so he plays his part. The sixth age shifts
Into the lean and slippered pantaloon,
With spectacles on nose and pouch on side;
His youthful hose, well saved, a world too wide
For his shrunk shank, and his big manly voice,
Turning again toward childish treble, pipes
And whistles in his sound. Last scene of all,
That ends this strange eventful history,
Is second childishness and mere oblivion,
Sans teeth, sans eyes, sans taste, sans everything.” ― William Shakespeare

node.text: Here’s another favourite image from my trip to Namibia this year. One of those crazy places that make photography so much fun. The place is called Solitaire and it is in the middle of the desert. Needless to say, it also has an awesome bakery just a few meters away. Who would guess it from this angle? ;-) Looking to see some of these awesome places for yourself? Look no further than @DiscoveryPhotoTours. Namibia is just one of the places we take you!

The shipwreck of the SS Maheno on beautiful Fraser Island in #Australia. I really want to revisit this incredible place once day. Truly one of the most unique and special places I've ever seen.

Visiting Namibia was one of the absolute highlights of my travel year. This epic location is called the Deadvlei and is another Unesco World Heritage sites that I had the privilege to visit. 
The trees died, as there no longer was enough water to survive. The remaining skeletons of the trees, which are believed to have died 600–700 years ago (1340- 1430), are now black because the intense sun has scorched them. Though not petrified, the wood does not decompose because it is so dry.

After a fun and successful trip to Photokina this September, I was lucky enough to get to travel to Paris and revisit one of my favourite areas of the city.
The La Défense business district is not the Paris most people think of when they do think of Paris. The modern architecture district was built up starting in 1958 and has recently undergone a major transformation including the beautiful new Tour D2 (D2 Tower) you see in the middle left of this image.
It always is nice to find unexpected treasures where you least expect them. 
I lucked out with the perfect weather for the few days I was in the La Défense area and have a whole new series of Paris images I can't wait to edit.

Wishing all my Jordanian friends all the best on their national holiday. Jordan is one of my favourite places in the world and for good reason. While the historic sites are breathtaking and natural beauty is out of this world, it truly is the people that make the country so special. I always look forward to the next time I'm able to visit and run another photo tour there. 
Getting my tour groups the unique opportunity to capture unique images like this one of the Monastery in Petra is part of the overall life experience that I'm proud to share with people on my @dreamphototours. I'm not sure what I like more; being there in some of the most amazing places on the planet, or seeing the expressions on people's faces as they experience the majestic beauty of Jordan for the first time. Getting the chance to photograph this two-thousand-year-old site under the stars with just my tour participants (and no one else) was one of the best photography moments of my life. 
On May 25, 1946, the end of the British Mandate over Transjordan was approved by the UN. On that date, Transjordan became an independent sovereign state as the Hashemite Kingdom of Transjordan. In 1948, it was renamed the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan.

Once again... Happy Birthday, Jordan!

One of my favorite photos from my first trip to Italy is this image of The Papal Basilica of St Paul Outside the Walls in Rome. Out of all the churches I was able to visit in Rome I have to say that this one was the most impressive, even more so than Saint Peter’s Basilica. The lavish details in the floors, pillars, ceilings, windows and walls was astounding. Both inside and out this place makes one stand in awe of what architects and artisans of the time were capable of without the use of modern technology.
Another awesome sunset in central #Florida. Have a great weekend!
One of the coolest and most unique waterfalls I've ever seen was on a walk through Maligne Canyon in Jasper National Park in Alberta. #explorealberta #explorecanada

node.text:
Waking up bright and early is the only way to avoid the hordes of people at popular spots like the Spanish Steps in #Rome.
I can't get enough of this beautiful city and keep going back on a yearly basis. 
What are your favorite cities to photograph?
Thar she blows!! The famous geyser near the village of Geysir in #Iceland ❄️

Land of the lost... That title always comes to mind when I remember this hauntingly timeless place that we literally stumbled upon in #Iceland Wishing I was back there right now during a hot and sticky heat wave here in Montreal.

Sometimes I am grateful for the rain because it keeps everyone out of my photos. This is a great example of what I'm talking about. The square at Napoleon's tomb at Les Invalides in #Paris was remarkably devoid of people on this rainy afternoon. 😃
One of the hidden photographic treasures of #Tokyo; the "Medusa" underpass is a great place to get a cool photo from an interesting vantage point. #Japan

Just another beautiful morning sunrise in Innsbruck. I only had a brief time there but loved my tour of #Austria. I was lucky to see Vienna and Salzburg as well as Innsbruck and I've since added a few other Austrian destinations to my bucket list.
Even the police in #Milan are ultra fashion conscious. And nowhere more so than at the beautiful Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II right next to the iconic Milan Cathedral. #Italy #travel
Just another beautiful sunset in #Florida. Missing the warm weather, good seafood, and time at the beach. ☀️🌴😃

Waking up bright and early is the only way to see someone me of the world's most beautiful historic sites if you want them all to yourself. Every time I go to #Rome I try to do just that and get to one of the countless spectacular locations before sunrise. This was shot earlier this year on my annual #Italy photo tour. I'm doing it again next year... Join me!

We literally had the keys to the castle here at Klis Fortress in beautiful Croatia. Arriving at dawn would have been too early since the giant gates at the front are locked at that time. However, our intrepid guide Daniel from @pluratravel managed to get us the keys for our early morning shoot... Pure awesomeness 😃

Serenity is the word that comes to mind when I think back to this moment in the Bamboo Forest in Kyoto. It was blissful listening to the sound of the wind knocking the trees together as I walked around looking for interesting angles to photograph. Yup, just the sound of the wind... And the dude with the gasoline powered leaf blower... Le sigh

Alcazar de Segovia. It rained the whole time I was in Segovia. Well, the whole time minus ten minutes or so when I was able to get this shot. I need to get back there and finish what I went to photograph. One day! #spain #castle

Can you guess where this photo was taken?
Check out my takeover of the @aboutdotme Instagram feed this week. Head over to their feed to see some of my favorite shots. I also did an interview with them on their blog: bt.me/igkenktravel

Taking over @aboutdotme's Instagram feed for the week. Head over to their feed to see some of my favorite shots. 
This is one of my favourite travel moments. Petra is one of the world's most stunning locations so it's no wonder that it is a United Nations world heritage site and Wonder of the World. Interested in seeing it first hand? Join me this November when I lead a photo tour there with @dreamphototours 😃👍
St Paul's Cathedral in #London is a stunning church inside and out. So glad I had the chance to photograph it during a brief stay in the British capital last year.
The Hvita river in #Iceland. So sad that I won't be visiting Iceland this year but looking forward to a winter visit in 2016.

Another awe inspiring view in Plitvice national park in Croatia. There are more breathtaking waterfalls there than I could have ever imagined. So happy to have had the chance to experience this unique country thanks to my friends at @pluratravel

One of the most dramatic sunsets I have ever witnessed. The sky literally looked like it was on fire that evening in #dubrovnik. Thanks to @pluratravel for making this the trip to #croatia one I'll never forget.

One night in Bangkok on my awesome trip with #VikingCruises. This is the beautiful Wat Pho temple and shooting here on my last night in SE Asia was a great way to wrap up my trip. What made this trip even more special was flying on @cathaypacific in business... What a way to fly! #lifewelltravelled
It's a good thing that I threw a coin into the Trevi fountain when I first visited years ago. I've had the good fortune of returning five times since then. 🇮🇹😃👍
The Hungarian State Opera House in beautiful Budapest is one of the most stunning interiors of any building I've ever seen and photographed.
Seljalandsfoss in #Iceland is one of the coolest waterfalls I have ever seen. How many waterfalls can you walk around in a 360 degree circle?
One of my favourite places in the word is Jokulsarlon in Iceland. The ever-changing land and sea scape allows you to get unique images each and every time you photograph this beautiful location.

Beautiful Vernazza on the Italian Riviera in CinqueTerre. Just returned from there and tons of other awesome Italian destinations on my annual @dreamphototours Italy Tour.
Already looking forward to next year's tour. 📷😃🇮🇹🍷🍝🍕

Croatia was full of wonderful places to discover and was one of the highlights of my travels last year. The country is blessed with both historic and natural beauty. So much to see and photograph that two weeks just flew by.

This was shot at Krka National Park as the sun was setting. Most people had already left the park and it was lovely to just hear the rushing waterfalls and nothing else.

Thanks so much to Daniel from @pluratravel for the trip of a lifetime!

Serenity at sunrise on beautiful Lake Maligne in Banff National Park in Alberta, Canada. There is nothing quite like the crisp Rocky Mountain air to energize you for a day of exploring and photography. #explorealberta #explorecanada

One of the must see places when visiting beautiful Croatia is Krka National Park. Croatia was such an awesome experience in so many ways and I was blown away with how diverse the landscapes were. Magical forests, innumerable waterfalls, and seascapes galore. I can't wait to return to continue discovering all the treasures that Croatia has to offer travellers. Thanks to @pluratravel for making my Croatia visit the best it could be!
This brought back memories of one of my favourite albums. Can your guess which one?
Gazing at the heavens in beautiful Alberta, Canada.
Can you guess where this is? 😉
One of the places that has to be considered as one of the planet's natural wonders is Plitvice National Park with n Croatia. This is just one of the reasons why.
I ❤️ NY 😊

node.text: Another Frank Gehry architectural masterpiece. Can you guess where this is? 😉
Memories of warm summer days in #Toronto.

Guards protecting the crown at the parliament building in Budapest. This is one of the most beautiful buildings in the world and if you ever find yourself in the Hungarian capital,  do yourselves a favor and check it out.

If you've always wanted to visit #Iceland and photograph locations like this spectacular waterfall (Gullfoss), then why not join me and @difruscia for the trip of a lifetime.  http://bit.ly/Iceland-PhotoTour

We are heading back to Iceland in May 2015 for a 10 day photography tour of this beautiful island nation. This time we are covering the whole island as we circle the nation on the famous ring road. Ahhh to be returning to this glorious location again feels like going home! and this is just one of the awesome places that we get a chance to photograph. Waterfalls, geysers, glacial lagoons, ice formations on the beach, lava fields, and so much more. Hope to see you in Iceland in May :-)
BMW world in Munich. Such a cool series if buildings and hey, they even have a few cars inside ;)
Heading back to beautiful #Italy on Monday. I'm off to Turin but this magical place is Manarola in Cinque Terre.
Cloud Gate at Millennium Park in #Chicago. Love, love, love the Chicago #architecture.
Lake Pierce in beautiful central #Florida
The White House in Washington D.C. at sunset. Glad I was able to get this shot off before the police told me to stop using my tripod.
Upper Kananaskis Lake in beautiful Alberta, Canada. Alberta truly is one of the most beautiful spots on Earth and I'm counting the days until my return. @travelalberta #explorealberta
Kinkakuji... The golden temple in Kyoto. One of the highlights of my trip to Japan.
Walking through the bamboo forest in #Kyoto
One of the most stunning sunsets I have witnessed in the last few years and in one of my favourite cities in the world. An illuminated St Peters basilica in Vatican City.
Our stop this morning was Kirkjufellfoss at Grundarfjörður in western Iceland. I'm excited to have this photo of mine appearing in a National Geographic later this year!

Feeling awesome here in beautiful Banff National Park. I can't believe how incredibly beautiful my own country is and I wish that I could spend more time exploring Canada. The photo is from our sunrise shoot at Lake Louise here in Alberta.... I'm in love with this place! @travelalberta
Awesome to be back in beautiful Alberta for a ten day photographic journey. Thanks @travelalberta for making it happen!
